Cell["2.4 Poisson Distribution", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->GrayLevel[0],
 TextAlignment->Center,
 FontSize->14,
 FontWeight->"Bold"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The last member of the collection of single-variable discrete distributions \
that we will look at is the ",
 StyleBox["Poisson distribution",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ".  It arises as a model for random variables that count the number of \
occurrences of an event in a given region of space or time, such as the \
number of users of a computer lab during a fixed time period, the number of \
dandelions in a yard, the number of dust particles in a room, the number of \
cars arriving to an intersection in a fixed time period, etc.  Its state \
space is the non-negative integers ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"0", ",", "1", ",", "2", ",", "..."}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", and the probability mass function that characterizes it is in formula (1) \
below.  So, this distribution depends on a single parameter called \[Mu], \
hence, we refer to it as the Poisson(\[Mu]) distribution.  \n\tIn the cases \
of the other discrete distributions that we have studied, the mass function \
of the associated random variable was derivable from primitive assumptions \
about the randomness of an experiment.  The Poisson distribution is a bit \
different, since it comes up as an idealization of a binomial experiment \
whose number of trials approaches infinity while the success probability \
becomes vanishingly small.  To see the idea, consider some event that happens \
sporadically on a time axis, in such a way that the chance that it happens \
during a short time interval is proportional to the length of the interval, \
and the events that it happens in each of two disjoint time intervals are \
independent.  Without loss of generality, let the time axis be the bounded \
interval ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"[", 
    RowBox[{"0", ",", "1"}], "]"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", and also let \[Mu] be the proportionality constant, that is, P[event \
happens in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"[", 
    RowBox[{"a", ",", "b"}], "]"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 "] = ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[Mu]", "(", 
    RowBox[{"b", "-", "a"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ". Then, if the time interval [0, 1] is broken up into ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " disjoint, equally sized subintervals [0, 1/",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "], ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["(", TraditionalForm]]],
 "1/",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", 2/",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "], ...,  ((",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"n", "-", "1"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ")/",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", 1],"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.42487650590625*^9, {3.425126647416*^9, 3.4251266688380003`*^9}, {
   3.4362208190825434`*^9, 3.436220819086543*^9}, 3.4564985339982*^9}],

