Cell[TextData[{
 "\tIn summary, the Poisson distribution is an approximation for the binomial \
distribution with large ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["n", TraditionalForm]]],
 " and small ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["p", TraditionalForm]]],
 ", and the Poisson parameter relates to these by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[Mu]", "=", 
    RowBox[{"n", " ", "p"}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ".\n\t",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " has an object for the Poisson distribution, called \n\n\t\t\t\t\
PoissonDistribution[\[Mu]]\n\t\nwhich can be used in the usual way with the \
RandomInteger, PDF, and CDF functions.  Let us use it to see how close the \
binomial distribution is to the Poisson distribution for large ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and small ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". We take ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = 100, \[Mu] = 4, and ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = \[Mu]/",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = 4/100. You will be asked to extend the investigation to other values of \
the parameters in the exercises. First is a table of the first few values of \
the Poisson and binomial p.m.f.'s, followed by superimposed connected list \
plots. "
}], "Text"],

