Cell[TextData[{
 "\tBy our earlier discussion of the domain of application of the Poisson \
distribution, it is reasonable to assume that as long as the probability of \
an occurrence in a short interval is proportional to the length of the \
interval, and the numbers of occurrences on disjoint intervals are \
independent, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "t"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " should have a Poisson distribution.  \n\tWhat should be the parameter of \
this Poisson distribution? Let \[Lambda] be the expected number of \
occurrences per unit time, i.e., ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["E",
      FontSlant->"Plain"], "[", 
     SubscriptBox["X", "1"], "]"}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ". In a time interval of length ",
 StyleBox["t",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " such as [0, ",
 StyleBox["t",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "] we should expect \[Lambda]\[CenterDot]",
 StyleBox["t",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " occurrences. Thus, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["E",
      FontSlant->"Plain"], "[", 
     SubscriptBox["X", "t"], "]"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"\[Lambda]", " ", "t"}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " and since the expected value of a Poisson random variable is the same as \
its parameter, it makes sense that  ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "t"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " \[Tilde] Poisson(\[Lambda] ",
 StyleBox["t",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "). The constant \[Lambda] is called the ",
 StyleBox["rate of the process",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ".\n\tAll of this can be put on a rigorous footing, but we will not do that ",
 StyleBox["until later",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 ". After we study a continuous distribution called the ",
 StyleBox["exponential distribution",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", we will be able to define a Poisson process constructively, by supposing \
that the times between successive occurrences ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["T", "n"], TraditionalForm]]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{" ", 
    RowBox[{"-", " "}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["T", 
    RowBox[{"n", "-", "1"}]], TraditionalForm]]],
 " are independent and have a common exponential distribution.  For now \
though, we will simply assume that certain situations generate a Poisson \
process, which means a family ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    FormBox[
     SubscriptBox["X", "t"],
     TraditionalForm], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " of random variables for which ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "t"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " has the Poisson(\[Lambda]",
 StyleBox["t",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ") distribution and whose sample paths are as in Figure 13. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.425080380993142*^9, 3.425080682858142*^9}, {
  3.42512733452*^9, 3.425127342524*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Activity 4",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "  Many examples of Poisson processes revolve around service situations, \
where the occurrence times are arrival times of customers.  Give some \
examples of such situations, and discuss what the underlying assumptions must \
be in order that a Poisson process is a good model for the cumulative number \
of customers as a function of time. "
}], "Text",
 CellFrame->True],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Example 2",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "  Suppose that cars travelling on an expressway arrive to a toll station \
according to a Poisson process with rate \[Lambda] = 5 per minute. Thus, we \
are assuming that the numbers of cars arriving in disjoint time intervals are \
independent, and the probability of an arrival in a short time interval is \
proportional to the length of the interval.  Let ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "t"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " be the total number of cars in [0, ",
 StyleBox["t",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "].  Find: (a) ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["P",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "[", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["X", "2"], ">", " ", "8"}], "]"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ";  (b) ",
 Cell[BoxData[
